Amending the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which underpins the euro by setting constraints determining the size of budget deficits of Union members, is in danger.
Germany, heavyweight of the Union, has failed to keep its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
In addition, she used her political weight to cover up the warning signs of her deficit, set up by the European Commission according to the terms of the stability pact.
Today it's France who plays the bad guys.
The number two of the Union, little enthusiastic, in turn officially declares not being able to keep its promise of reducing the budget deficit, a year after small Ireland received an official warning about its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the stability pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems very affected by the discussions aiming to abolish it, as well as the discussions aiming to amend it.
And rightly so: the pact is badly conceived and its implementation poorly done.
Limiting the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and disregards the fact that deficits increase automatically when the economy slows down.
Admitting this fact, the architects of the pact have poisoned the situation by adopting two poorly thought-out solutions.
They introduced a safeguard clause allowing any country to suspend its budget limits in the event of a significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is practically impossible in fact.
Concerned that serious slowdowns could breach the deficit ceiling, they declared that a normal deficit equaled zero deficit.
Therefore, each year, each country must submit a projection budget for the two years to come, showing how the fiscal balance will be achieved in its time.
The German commitment for 2002 was taken in 2001, when its economy was developing at a reasonable rate.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from reaching its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, decided reasonably not to exacerbate the situation by adopting a contractionary fiscal policy.
The Commission, seeking to project itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be taken by real politicians, the Council of Ministers of Finance.
Nobody wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognised that they could all be confronted with the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation in France is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, particularly on lowering tax burdens.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it is not just a question of showing political intelligence, it is also a question of showing economic intelligence, as long as budgetary spending is also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain state-funded privileges, and as a result, budget cuts are definitely poorly perceived.
So, France cannot meet its targets and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has mastered the art of defying the laws of the Union.
Political manoeuvres will surely follow.
Economists and cynics are hardly surprised.
The objective of the pact, putting in place a fiscal discipline within countries sharing the same currency, is entirely acceptable.
However, the loss of control of their national monetary policy, members of the Union now benefit only from a single macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine a long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The Stability Pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the objective of the 3% imposed by Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians accordingly.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look very far.
Monetary policy faces the same challenge.
She must stabilize prices in the long term, while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
These past ten years, monetary policy has experienced a real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it's enough to delegate this policy to a competent group, the Central Bank, by giving it the necessary political independence, and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that all mistakes will have to be settled in the future, it's up to him to show some common sense.
This has proven to be one of the major improvements in the monetary field over the past few years.
The same approach should work for tax policy.
Some, of course, fear losing it in terms of democracy.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different goals.
The first one is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure, both in terms of expenditures and in terms of revenues.
Decisions on these matters cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and oversight.
The second is macroeconomic: it involves defining the budget balance to manage fluctuation cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent agency.
Thus, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term goal is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure the outcome, the status of such a Committee and its mandates must be the subject of consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulation, without any political decision-making, but simply relying on good common sense.
